<h2>Overview — why this partner is useful</h2>
<p>A neighbourhood redesign is easy to soften into something that pleases everyone and decides nothing. The Urban Planner refuses that. It makes the strongest honest case for density and housing supply, so that when your plan protects green space or limits height, you are doing it against a real argument rather than a strawman. The point is not to obey it. The point is to <strong>synthesise its push against the Equity &amp; Resilience Partner's push</strong> and own the trade-off you land on.</p>
<p>Like every partner in this course, it can be <strong>confidently wrong about quantitative claims</strong> (densities, housing numbers, cost figures). That is deliberate: catching a specific wrong number is exactly the "one thing the AI got wrong" move your <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation</a> needs.</p>

<h2>Pairs with</h2>
<p><strong><a href="/ai-partners/equity-resilience-partner/">The Equity &amp; Resilience Partner</a></strong> — the deliberate counterweight. Run both. The Urban Planner pushes to build and intensify; the Equity &amp; Resilience Partner pushes for green-blue space, flood and heat protection, and the people who could be displaced. Your plan is the synthesis you can defend.</p>

